Development of travel prices since 1989
By 1989, there were only five government travel agencies approved in the ČSSR, Čedok, sports urist, CKM, Recrea and Carturist.
The travel offices sold mainly trips to the socialist East Block Countries, in the West, only chosen at that time.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the DDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia launched a prowest course and therefore the journeys to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the eastern block (also the Czechoslovakia) were allowed to travel freely within the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travels were not possible.
The travel offices already offered travel to the West, but they had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag before the travel office, or at least have "good acquaintance" in the travel office.
Even so, the thing hadn't been running for a long time.
The so-called devisenzusage - the condition for a trip to the West - was given only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a free exchangeable currency, so it would not have been possible to make the necessary financial resources (western currency) for a journey to the West without a currency allowance.
The majority of the Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates – a habit that lasts until today.
The total revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on the foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, which one is no longer aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of the 1990s, the devising obligation was lifted up in the neighbouring western European countries, causing a huge wave of short visits especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovakia could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there at least a few days.
The Czech vacationers slept on traveling to Paris in the tent in the park, because who had already had the money for a accommodation in the hotel or in a guesthouse.
A typical feature of foreign trips from Czechs was at that time a full-packed trunk room with conserves, beer and durable worst, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists could finally buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of life and thus the average salaries increased, which in 1997 came into another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demands for travel, after 1997, travel agencies started to prepare regular travels through charter flights, making flights incredibly approved thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantity discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already devised payments with all the highly developed countries in the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-off" travel, it came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight was made to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, every year, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying in far-reached sunny countries; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel annually in exotic countries!
Another significant moment in the epoch, which marked our postrevolutionary development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the USA raised the visa obligation for Czech tourists, which definitively formed our country among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008 the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than 15 Tsd. CZK per head for a single holiday stay including the cost of the holiday resort.
