Asphalt by UNAM prevents holes
Rafael Herrera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM developed with polymers modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs that go out of the street were not considered, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200 000 holes when the rainy period in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (City Area of the Valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera Nájera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, warned and assured that if the expulsion and maintenance of the asphaltment were adequately damaged, the number of strokes are significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Stagelöcher from a technical point of view", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory, for which he is responsible, developed with polymer-modified asphalts to produce a similar mixture of asphalt, which, however, has a greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Mrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalts in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, should be used to improve the behaviour of the road basin and thus avoid the emergence of holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the worst part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, of which part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part is low - the so-called malthenes. Together, they give the road cover its characteristic tehelastic behavior.
Zähelastic behaviour of the asphalt means that at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C, it is very tough and almost fixed at 50°C, while it is breached at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the streets is not equal, but changes on a day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer reported.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City would have a flexible road cover, consisting of six material layers, of which the last three asphalts included.
Between the upper layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalted and then fortified stones.
Each single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles are continued to move on it and powers are produced, this layer allows a good distribution of force in the street.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he said, "a last layer is laid out, the so-called drag layer consisting of tiny stones, i.e. of sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical strength than the wear layer and it needs to produce friction.
The majority of forces receive and distributed by this road cover also needs an appropriate thickness and the material from which it consists must be retained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to be taken into account, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
